    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-12-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-12-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="594"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d594">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77/2366</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Herrick</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-12-16">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 16, 1921</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received December 29.]</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 986</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In reply to the Department’s Instruction No. 93
                    of November 2nd, relative to the present status of the Russo-Asiatic Bank, I
                    have the honor to report that from inquiry at the Foreign Office I learn that
                    the present status of the bank is uncertain. The reorganization mentioned in the
                    Department’s dispatch was carried out and the bank is in possession of a fair
                    amount of funds. The French Government intended at one time to make it a French
                    institution, but found that there were certain disadvantages connected with such
                    a course of action and they have since been marking time, feeling that it would
                    be more desirable to carry on as at present and leave the final settlement of
                    its status until the whole question of the Russian banks comes up for
                    international discussion with the reestablishment of Russia.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Myron T. Herrick</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
